revision.text:
{{also|eiþer}}
==English==
===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₂ey-|*kʷ-|*-teros}}
From {{inh|en|enm|either}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ǣġhwæþer}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|-}}, ultimately corresponding to {{m|en|ay||always, ever}} + {{m|en|whether}}. Akin to Old Saxon {{m|osx|eogihwethar}}, {{m|osx|iahwethar}} (Low German {{m|nds|jeed}}); Old Dutch {{m|odt|*iogewether}}, {{m|odt|*iowether}}, {{m|odt|*iother}} (Dutch {{m|nl|ieder}}); Old High German {{m|goh|eogihwedar}}, {{m|goh|iegihweder}}, {{m|goh|ieweder}} (German {{m|de|jeder}}).
===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|ī′''th''ə(r)|ē′''th''ə(r)}} {{IPA|en|/ˈaɪ.ðə(ɹ)/|/ˈiː.ðə(ɹ)/}}
** {{audio|en|en-uk-either.ogg|Audio (UK)}}, {{audio|en|en-us-either.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|aɪðə(ɹ)|iːðə(ɹ)|s=2}}
* {{q|obsolete (in use until the 20th c.)}} {{enPR|ā′''th''ə(r)}} {{IPA|en|/ˈeɪ.ðə(ɹ)/}}
* In the UK, {{IPAchar|/aɪ/}} is used more in Southern England, and {{IPAchar|/iː/}} is more usual in Northern England. In North America, {{IPAchar|/iː/}} is the most common, but {{IPAchar|/aɪ/}} is predominant in some regions. Note that even if one pronunciation is more common in a region, the pronunciation used varies by individual speaker and sometimes by situation. {{IPAchar|/eɪ/}} was once heard in Northern England, but has now largely fallen into disuse.<ref>"Pronunciation: Either". Reader's Digest. (1964). ''The Complete Atlas of the British Isles'', p. 123.</ref>
===Determiner===
{{en-det}}
# Any one (of two).
#: {{ux|en|You can have it in '''either''' colour.}}
# Each of two; both. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|There is a locomotive at '''either''' end of the train, one pulling and the other pushing.}}
#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|book=3|passage=His flowing hair <br> In curls on '''either''' cheek played.}}
#* '''1936''', {{w|Djuna Barnes}}, ''{{w|Nightwood}}'', Faber & Faber 2007, page 31:
#*: Her hands, long and beautiful, lay on '''either''' side of her face.
# {{lb|en|now|rare}} Any one (of more than two).
#* {{RQ:Richardson Clarissa|letter=51|text=They ''entreat'', they ''pray'', they ''beg'', they ''supplicate'' (will '''either''' of these do, Miss Clary?) that you will make no scruple to go to your uncle Antony's {{…}}.}}
====Usage notes====
* When there are more than two alternatives, in the sense of “one of many”, {{m|en|any}} is now generally used instead.
====Synonyms====
* {{sense|each of two}} {{l|en|both}}, {{l|en|each}}
