===Conjunction===
{{en-con}}
# {{n-g|Introduces the first of two (or occasionally more) options or possibilities, the second (or last) of which is introduced by “[[or]]”}}.
#: '''''Either''' you eat your dinner or you go to your room.''
#: ''You can have '''either''' potatoes or rice with that, but not both.''
#: {{ux|en|You'll be '''either''' early, late, or on time.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 5, 2006|title=[http://www.usatoday.com/life/people/2006-12-05-mason_x.htm Mason drops lawsuit vs. Jews for Jesus]|work=USA Today|passage=You can't be a table and a chair. You're '''either''' a Jew or a gentile.|quotee={{w|Jackie Mason}}}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1893|author={{w|Walter Besant}}|title=[http://gutenberg.org/ebooks/34738 The Ivory Gate]|chapter=Prologue|passage=Thus, when he drew up instructions in lawyer language{{...}}his clerks{{...}}understood him very well. If he had written a love letter, or a farce, or a ''ballade'', or a story, no one, '''either''' clerks, or friends, or compositors, would have understood anything but a word here and a word there.}}
